content.description: Side pull sit start into a series of wide pitches with a long reach to the top. Lots of potential on the west facing side of the boulder, if willing to put in the working moving the fallen tree.
content.location: Almost on the banks of Cedar Creek.

content.description: Start of east facing side pull and move onto the south facing sloper rail. Then, work up.
content.location: South facing between Boss Man Mayor and Becky's Bible

climbs.name: River is Up and Road is Closed

content.description: Sit start on left side pull. Work into compression with left along left side pulls and right on right edge. Work up until top.
content.location: To the right (west) of Becky's Bible. North facing. In pile of boulders at base of bluffs.

content.description: Sit start. Left hand in pocket and right along the side, work up.
content.location: Same boulder as Boss Man Mayor just on east facing side.

content.description: Take a shot of whiskey and unbutton your shirt for this highball off-width. Clean crack with a dirty top out, just like a midnight bar lover.
content.protection: Bring your finest spotter and biggest pads.
content.location: On the eastern side (left when looking at the overlook from the bottom) of the cliffs near the small cave feature.

content.description: Sit start on the east facing pockets.
content.location: On the west side of the overlook boulders near creek banks.

content.description: Sit start on south facing pockets work up into the slopers and jugs along the spine ridge.
content.location: Midway between cliff base and Cedar Creek.

content.description: Slab start into crawling along the jug spine.
content.location: In a pile of boulders near the base of the bluffs. Left (east) of River is Up and Road is Closed. North facing toward Cedar Creek.

content.description: Below the overlook platform, on the main trail above, lie a dozen or so free-standing sandstone boulders ranging in heights from 6-14ft. There is alsoÂ plenty of potential for sporting climbing along the cliffs and bouldering on the cliff base.
